[ Silence ]

00:00:06.210 --> 00:00:07.610
&gt;&gt; Eleanor Billington: Hi,
everyone, good morning.

00:00:07.610 --> 00:00:08.910
&gt;&gt; Good morning.

00:00:08.910 --> 00:00:10.210
&gt;&gt; Eleanor Billington: Good
morning, [laughs] good morning.

00:00:10.210 --> 00:00:11.700
We are so happy that
you all are here.

00:00:11.700 --> 00:00:13.000
Thank you for joining us.

00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:15.360
Welcome to the 2016
National Book Festival

00:00:15.360 --> 00:00:17.180
in the Poetry and Prose Pavilion.

00:00:17.180 --> 00:00:20.220
This pavilion is sponsored by the
National Endowment for the Arts,

00:00:20.220 --> 00:00:22.180
our nation's arts agency.

00:00:22.180 --> 00:00:25.350
And the NEA we are currently
celebrating our 50th anniversary.

00:00:25.350 --> 00:00:28.840
So we are celebrating years of
giving Americans the opportunity

00:00:28.840 --> 00:00:32.120
to participate in the arts,
exercise their imaginations,

00:00:32.120 --> 00:00:34.450
and develop their creative
capacities.

00:00:34.450 --> 00:00:37.820 position:56%
On behalf of everyone at the Arts
Endowment, thank you for joining us.

00:00:37.820 --> 00:00:39.130
I'm Eleanor Billington.

00:00:39.130 --> 00:00:42.380
I manage the Poetry Out Loud
Program at the Arts Endowment.

00:00:42.380 --> 00:00:45.240
Poetry Out Loud is a national
youth arts program that seeks

00:00:45.240 --> 00:00:48.760
to foster the next generation of
literary readers by capitalizing

00:00:48.760 --> 00:00:52.510
on the latest trends in poetry,
recitation and performance.

00:00:52.510 --> 00:00:54.830
Poetry Out Loud encourages
high school students to learn

00:00:54.830 --> 00:00:56.890
about classic and contemporary
poetry

00:00:56.890 --> 00:00:59.670
through memorization
and public recitation.

00:00:59.670 --> 00:01:03.070
Started in 2005 as a partnership
between the National Endowment

00:01:03.070 --> 00:01:06.900
for the Arts, the Poetry
Foundation, Chicago, and 53 state

00:01:06.900 --> 00:01:09.960
and jurisdictional art agencies,
Poetry Out Loud has grown

00:01:09.960 --> 00:01:13.720
to serve more than three million
students and 45,000 teachers

00:01:13.720 --> 00:01:15.390
at 10,000 high schools nationwide.

00:01:15.390 --> 00:01:17.170
We are really proud of its growth.

00:01:17.170 --> 00:01:20.420
The program helps students
master public speaking skills,

00:01:20.420 --> 00:01:22.000
and build self confidence.

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:26.060
But most importantly, it helps them
discover their own creative voice.

00:01:26.060 --> 00:01:28.400
If poetry recitation sounds
a little bit dry to you,

00:01:28.400 --> 00:01:30.090
I promise that in a few minutes,

00:01:30.090 --> 00:01:34.080
you're going to see firsthand
the power of a poem spoken aloud.

00:01:34.080 --> 00:01:36.360
A little bit about the way
the program is structured;

00:01:36.360 --> 00:01:37.660
we use a pyramid structure,

00:01:37.660 --> 00:01:39.220
so it's a lot like the
National Spelling Bee.

00:01:39.220 --> 00:01:41.430
Poetry Out Loud starts
at the classroom level.

00:01:41.430 --> 00:01:44.300
Winners in the classroom then
advance to a school competition,

00:01:44.300 --> 00:01:46.940
then to a state and regional
competition, and ultimately,

00:01:46.940 --> 00:01:48.580
they come to the national finals,

00:01:48.580 --> 00:01:51.070
which is held in Washington,
DC each spring.

00:01:51.070 --> 00:01:53.310
If you're an interested high
school student in the audience,

00:01:53.310 --> 00:01:55.660
talk with your teachers
about Poetry Out Loud.

00:01:55.660 --> 00:01:58.230
And if you're an interested high
school teacher in the audience,

00:01:58.230 --> 00:02:00.600
please consider taking on
Poetry Out Loud this year.

00:02:00.600 --> 00:02:02.250
It is not too late to get involved.

00:02:02.250 --> 00:02:05.010
We have information on the side
of the room about the program,

00:02:05.010 --> 00:02:08.360
so come talk to me or anyone at
that table after our session.

00:02:08.360 --> 00:02:10.530
We also have a great website
dedicated to the program.

00:02:10.530 --> 00:02:12.360
I know everybody has
smart phones now.

00:02:12.360 --> 00:02:14.460
So if you go to poetryoutloud.org,

00:02:14.460 --> 00:02:18.060
you can see the website includes
more than 900 eligible poems.

00:02:18.060 --> 00:02:20.330
We have video recitations,
we have many of the students

00:02:20.330 --> 00:02:21.850
on the stage featured
on that website.

00:02:21.850 --> 00:02:24.200
We also have a comprehensive
teachers guide,

00:02:24.200 --> 00:02:26.190
all free and available to you.

00:02:26.190 --> 00:02:29.130
We have -- again that
information is over here.

00:02:29.130 --> 00:02:30.730
So visit the table when we're done.

00:02:30.730 --> 00:02:34.830
Last year we had more than
315,000 students participate

00:02:34.830 --> 00:02:36.130
in Poetry Out Loud.

00:02:36.130 --> 00:02:38.460
And today you're going to hear
from three of the state champions

00:02:38.460 --> 00:02:41.080
who made it all the way
to the national finals.

00:02:41.080 --> 00:02:43.940
Poetry Out Loud students are
eligible for prizes at the state

00:02:43.940 --> 00:02:47.660
and national level of competition,
including a $20,000 prize

00:02:47.660 --> 00:02:49.050
for the national champion.

00:02:49.050 --> 00:02:53.200
Every year, Poetry Out Loud awards
more that $100,000 in prizes

00:02:53.200 --> 00:02:56.520
and school stipends for the
purchase of poetry materials.

00:02:56.520 --> 00:02:59.010
While a $20,000 prize
is nothing to scoff at,

00:02:59.010 --> 00:03:01.110
we believe that the
real reward comes

00:03:01.110 --> 00:03:04.590
when students connect their poems
to their own life experience.

00:03:04.590 --> 00:03:07.190
A successful poem can
challenge us, teach us,

00:03:07.190 --> 00:03:08.890
and invite us to view
our world anew.

00:03:08.890 --> 00:03:13.640
In the words of poet Naomi Shihab
Nye, "I love the deep attribution

00:03:13.640 --> 00:03:17.760
of poetry to pause, to look,
to listen, to pay attention

00:03:17.760 --> 00:03:20.820 position:56%
to variety, to learn something new."

00:03:20.820 --> 00:03:24.140 position:56%
This morning we have the opportunity
to slow down and really listen

00:03:24.140 --> 00:03:27.190
to these students, to honor
their work with our attention,

00:03:27.190 --> 00:03:31.560 position:56%
and to open ourselves to learning
from them and the poems they embody.

00:03:31.560 --> 00:03:33.080
So with that said, we're
going to get started.

00:03:33.080 --> 00:03:35.680
Our first student is Nealy Seams.

00:03:35.680 --> 00:03:39.940
Nealy is the 2016 Poetry Out Loud
state champion from West Virginia.

00:03:39.940 --> 00:03:42.270
She was one of the top
nine national finalists

00:03:42.270 --> 00:03:43.650
at this year's competition in DC.

00:03:43.650 --> 00:03:47.590
She's a recent graduate of
Greenbrier East High School,

00:03:47.590 --> 00:03:51.790 position:56%
and is attending Marshall University
in Huntington, West Virginia,

00:03:51.790 --> 00:03:53.310
where she studies theater.

00:03:53.310 --> 00:03:56.510
Please join me in welcoming
