00:04:03.680 --> 00:04:07.300
&gt;&gt; Being in a competition
like Poetry Out Loud seems

00:04:07.300 --> 00:04:11.150
like it would be a lonely
experience to those looking in.

00:04:11.150 --> 00:04:12.710
But it's not.

00:04:12.710 --> 00:04:18.090 position:56%
Sure, you're up onstage by yourself,
but whenever you're backstage,

00:04:18.090 --> 00:04:22.510
you're making friends with people
who think the same way you do,

00:04:22.510 --> 00:04:24.200
and like the same things,

00:04:24.200 --> 00:04:29.960 position:56%
and are feeling the exact same thing
you are at the exact same time.

00:04:29.960 --> 00:04:31.510
Especially at the national level,

00:04:31.510 --> 00:04:34.860
you can broaden your
outlook on life.

00:04:34.860 --> 00:04:38.760
It's a microcosm of the
diversity of America,

00:04:38.760 --> 00:04:41.710
and it's at your fingertips.

00:04:41.710 --> 00:04:45.580
Relating to the poems, and
the audience, and your peers

00:04:45.580 --> 00:04:48.930
that you're meeting is
a beautiful experience,

00:04:48.930 --> 00:04:51.770
and it widens your outlook on life.

00:04:51.770 --> 00:04:53.130
And that's the biggest thing

00:04:53.130 --> 00:04:56.340
that I've taken away
from Poetry Out Loud.

00:04:56.340 --> 00:04:58.610
I will be doing two poems.

00:04:58.610 --> 00:05:02.510 position:56%
My first one called "Degrees of Gray
in Philipsburg" by Richard Hugo.

00:05:02.510 --> 00:05:06.240
[ Silence ]

00:05:06.240 --> 00:05:10.390
"You might come here
Sunday on a whim.

00:05:10.390 --> 00:05:13.450
Say your life broke down.

00:05:13.450 --> 00:05:17.760
The last good kiss
you had was years ago.

00:05:17.760 --> 00:05:22.090
You walk these streets laid
out by the insane past,

00:05:22.090 --> 00:05:27.330
hotels that didn't last, bars
that did, the tortured try

00:05:27.330 --> 00:05:32.650
of local drivers to
accelerate their lives.

00:05:32.650 --> 00:05:35.630
Only churches are kept up.

00:05:35.630 --> 00:05:38.870
The jail turned 70 this year.

00:05:38.870 --> 00:05:43.550
The only prisoner is always
in, not knowing what he's done.

00:05:43.550 --> 00:05:49.180
The principle supporting
business now is rage,

00:05:49.180 --> 00:05:55.050
hatred of the various grays the
mountain sends, hatred of the mill,

00:05:55.050 --> 00:05:58.380
the Silver Bill repeal,
the best liked girls

00:05:58.380 --> 00:06:01.320
who leave each year for Butte.

00:06:01.320 --> 00:06:06.570
One good restaurant and bars
can't wipe the boredom out.

00:06:06.570 --> 00:06:14.000
The 1907 boom, eight going
silver mines, a dance floor built

00:06:14.000 --> 00:06:20.020
on springs, all memory
resolves itself in gaze,

00:06:20.020 --> 00:06:25.090
in panoramic green you know the
cattle eat, or two stacks high

00:06:25.090 --> 00:06:30.740
above the town, two dead kilns, the
huge mill in collapse for 50 years

00:06:30.740 --> 00:06:33.440
that won't fall finally down.

00:06:33.440 --> 00:06:35.870
[ Silence ]

00:06:35.870 --> 00:06:42.190
Isn't this your life, that ancient
kiss still burning out your eyes?

00:06:42.190 --> 00:06:44.600
Isn't this defeat so accurate,

00:06:44.600 --> 00:06:51.920 position:56%
the church bell simply seems a pure
announcement, ring and no one comes?

00:06:51.920 --> 00:06:55.160
Don't empty houses ring?

00:06:55.160 --> 00:06:59.140
Are magnesium and scorn
sufficient to support a town,

00:06:59.140 --> 00:07:04.150
not just Philipsburg, but towns
of towering blondes, good jazz

00:07:04.150 --> 00:07:06.440
and booze the world
will never let you have

00:07:06.440 --> 00:07:09.210
until the town you
came from dies inside?

00:07:09.210 --> 00:07:11.410
[ Silence ]

00:07:11.410 --> 00:07:13.790
Say no to yourself.

00:07:13.790 --> 00:07:18.180
The old man, 20 when the
jail was built, still laughs,

00:07:18.180 --> 00:07:21.040
although his lips collapse.

00:07:21.040 --> 00:07:26.210
'Someday soon,' he says, 'I'll
go to sleep and not wake up.'

00:07:26.210 --> 00:07:30.890
You tell him, 'No; you're
talking to yourself.'

00:07:30.890 --> 00:07:34.650
The car that brought
you here still runs.

00:07:34.650 --> 00:07:41.080 position:56%
And the money you buy lunch with, no
matter where it's mined, is silver.

00:07:41.080 --> 00:07:44.450
And the girl who serves
your food is slender

00:07:44.450 --> 00:07:46.510
and her red hair lights the wall'."

00:07:46.510 --> 00:07:49.510
[ Silence ]

00:07:49.510 --> 00:07:58.740
[ Applause ]

00:07:58.740 --> 00:08:00.040
Thank you.

00:08:00.040 --> 00:08:03.580
And my second poem is called
"Passing" by Toi Derricotte.

00:08:03.580 --> 00:08:10.410
"A professor invites me
to his 'Black Lit' class;

00:08:10.410 --> 00:08:13.220
they're reading Larson's 'Passing'.

00:08:13.220 --> 00:08:15.190
One of the black students says,

00:08:15.190 --> 00:08:19.340
'Sometimes light-skinned blacks
think they can fool other blacks,

00:08:19.340 --> 00:08:25.020
but I can always tell,'
looking right through me.

00:08:25.020 --> 00:08:29.380
After I tell them I am black,
I ask the class, 'Was I passing

00:08:29.380 --> 00:08:33.260
when I was just sitting
here before I told you?'

00:08:33.260 --> 00:08:35.420
A white woman shakes
her head desperately,

00:08:35.420 --> 00:08:39.300
as if I had deliberately
deceived her.

00:08:39.300 --> 00:08:43.230
She keeps examining my
face, then turning away

00:08:43.230 --> 00:08:46.660
as if she hopes I'll disappear.

00:08:46.660 --> 00:08:49.940
Why presume passing is
based on what I leave out,

00:08:49.940 --> 00:08:53.290
and not what she fills in?

00:08:53.290 --> 00:08:59.270
In one scene in the book, in
a restaurant, she's 'passing'.

00:08:59.270 --> 00:09:05.540
Though no one checked her at
the door, 'Hey, are you black?'

00:09:05.540 --> 00:09:10.110
My father, who looked
white, told me this story.

00:09:10.110 --> 00:09:13.200
Every year when he'd go to
get his driver's license,

00:09:13.200 --> 00:09:19.230 position:56%
the man at the window filling out
the form would ask, 'White or black,

00:09:19.230 --> 00:09:23.250
pencil poised, without looking up.

00:09:23.250 --> 00:09:29.920
My father wouldn't pass, but he
might use silence to trap a devil.

00:09:29.920 --> 00:09:34.440
When he didn't speak, the man
would look up at my father's face.

00:09:34.440 --> 00:09:38.950
'What did he write,'
my father quizzed me."

00:09:38.950 --> 00:09:40.750
Thank you.

00:09:40.750 --> 00:09:48.400
[ Applause ]

00:09:48.400 --> 00:09:49.700
