00:10:15.630 --> 00:10:17.430
Welcome, Marta.

00:10:17.430 --> 00:10:22.690
[ Applause ]

00:10:22.690 --> 00:10:25.180
&gt;&gt; I memorized my poem, but I
did not memorize my statement,

00:10:25.180 --> 00:10:27.850
so [laughs] hello, everyone.

00:10:27.850 --> 00:10:31.190
It's such an honor to be here
representing Georgia one more time,

00:10:31.190 --> 00:10:35.560
you know, at the Georgia Poetry Out
Loud at the National Book Festival,

00:10:35.560 --> 00:10:38.170
and to get to recite
alongside my fellow competitors

00:10:38.170 --> 00:10:39.670
from earlier this year.

00:10:39.670 --> 00:10:45.380
So winning second place at the 2016
competition was such a wonderful,

00:10:45.380 --> 00:10:47.510
indescribable experience.

00:10:47.510 --> 00:10:51.400
I remember being amazing at how
nice and welcoming everyone was.

00:10:51.400 --> 00:10:54.130
And, you know, we were all
supportive of each other.

00:10:54.130 --> 00:10:56.810
And I remember telling jokes
and dancing around backstage

00:10:56.810 --> 00:11:00.920
because we were so nervous;
[laughter] so as we were waiting

00:11:00.920 --> 00:11:02.970
for our names to be called.

00:11:02.970 --> 00:11:07.210
And most of all, I remember, you
know, walking out onstage time

00:11:07.210 --> 00:11:10.650
after time, just hoping that
reciting my poems as best

00:11:10.650 --> 00:11:11.950
as I could would be enough.

00:11:11.950 --> 00:11:13.250
And apparently, it was.

00:11:13.250 --> 00:11:18.900
So it was amazing, but however
magical it was to be onstage,

00:11:18.900 --> 00:11:22.700
I think one of the most memorable
parts was the after-party,

00:11:22.700 --> 00:11:25.480
not because it meant that
the competition was over,

00:11:25.480 --> 00:11:30.090
but on the contrary, it gave us
a new place to begin, you know?

00:11:30.090 --> 00:11:31.860
It was wonderful.

00:11:31.860 --> 00:11:33.800
I sang a snippet of
a song that I ended

00:11:33.800 --> 00:11:36.850
up releasing just a
month ago on my first EP.

00:11:36.850 --> 00:11:41.050
I heard original poetry that
left me absolutely awestruck just

00:11:41.050 --> 00:11:45.190
at the capacity of feeling what
I was witnessing in that room.

00:11:45.190 --> 00:11:47.280
You know, I heard monologues,
and poetry,

00:11:47.280 --> 00:11:48.840
and singing, and more poetry.

00:11:48.840 --> 00:11:51.780
And at one point, there was
some beat-boxing going on.

00:11:51.780 --> 00:11:57.430
I'm not entirely sure; am I right;
and, of course, more poetry.

00:11:57.430 --> 00:12:00.030
But it wasn't just a celebration
of what had come to pass,

00:12:00.030 --> 00:12:03.910 position:56%
it was a celebration of everything
that we had learned from each other.

00:12:03.910 --> 00:12:08.200
It was a final moment to let our
walls down and share our passion,

00:12:08.200 --> 00:12:12.170
creativity, and experience
this time not for competition,

00:12:12.170 --> 00:12:16.560 position:56%
but for no other reason than that we
wanted to share what we had created

00:12:16.560 --> 00:12:18.870
with people that we knew
would appreciate it,

00:12:18.870 --> 00:12:20.580
and we knew would love us for it.

00:12:20.580 --> 00:12:24.600
So the poems I'm reciting
today are the two poems

00:12:24.600 --> 00:12:26.580
that got me into the final three.

00:12:26.580 --> 00:12:30.180
"For The Young who Want To" by
Marge Piercy is especially relevant

00:12:30.180 --> 00:12:32.500
in my life, seeing
as an artist myself,

00:12:32.500 --> 00:12:35.630
I kind of encounter
this situation a lot.

00:12:35.630 --> 00:12:38.130
And "Mingus at the
Showplace", on the other hand,

00:12:38.130 --> 00:12:40.150
holds a special place in my heart.

00:12:40.150 --> 00:12:44.710
It takes a while to understand,
analyze and fully appreciate,

00:12:44.710 --> 00:12:48.100
but when you do, it's
really impossible to forget.

00:12:48.100 --> 00:12:52.650
So without further adieu, I will
be performing, "For The Young

00:12:52.650 --> 00:12:54.510
Who Want To" by Marge Piercy.

00:12:54.510 --> 00:12:57.260
[ Silence ]

00:12:57.260 --> 00:13:00.770
"Talent is what they say you have

00:13:00.770 --> 00:13:05.000
after the novel is published
and favorably reviewed.

00:13:05.000 --> 00:13:08.960
Beforehand what you have
is a tedious delusion,

00:13:08.960 --> 00:13:11.340
a hobby, like knitting.

00:13:11.340 --> 00:13:17.320
Work is what you have done
after the play is produced,

00:13:17.320 --> 00:13:20.130
and the audience claps.

00:13:20.130 --> 00:13:22.780
Before that friends keep asking

00:13:22.780 --> 00:13:27.760
when you are planning
to go out and get a job.

00:13:27.760 --> 00:13:31.140
Genius is what they know you had

00:13:31.140 --> 00:13:36.600
after the third volume
of remarkable poems.

00:13:36.600 --> 00:13:40.810
Earlier they accuse
you of withdrawing,

00:13:40.810 --> 00:13:46.200
ask why you don't have
a baby, call you a bum.

00:13:47.890 --> 00:13:53.170
The reason people want MFAs,
take workshops with fancy names

00:13:53.170 --> 00:13:57.170 position:56%
when all you can really learn is a
few techniques, typing instructions,

00:13:57.170 --> 00:14:02.780
and somebody else's mannerisms, is
that every artist lacks a license

00:14:02.780 --> 00:14:06.620
to hang on the wall,
like your optician,

00:14:06.620 --> 00:14:11.170
your vet proving you may be a
clumsy sadist whose fillings fall

00:14:11.170 --> 00:14:16.150
into the stew but you're
certified dentist.

00:14:16.150 --> 00:14:24.050
[Laughter] The real writer
is one who really writes.

00:14:24.050 --> 00:14:30.170
Talent is an invention like
phlogiston after the fact of fire.

00:14:30.170 --> 00:14:34.490
