00:14:47.820 --> 00:14:51.430
This will be "Mingus at the
Showplace" by William Matthews.

00:14:51.430 --> 00:14:53.840
[ Silence ]

00:14:53.840 --> 00:15:05.050
"I was miserable, of course, for I
was 17, and so I swung into action

00:15:05.050 --> 00:15:09.880
and wrote a poem, and
it was miserable,

00:15:09.880 --> 00:15:13.520
for that was how I
thought poetry worked,

00:15:13.520 --> 00:15:17.170
you digested experience
and shat literature.

00:15:17.170 --> 00:15:24.710
It was 1960 at The Showplace, long
since defunct, on West 4th Street,

00:15:24.710 --> 00:15:29.480
and I sat at the bar, casting beer
money from a thin reel of ones,

00:15:29.480 --> 00:15:33.360
the kid in the city,
big ears like a puppy.

00:15:34.400 --> 00:15:38.570
And I knew Mingus was a genius.

00:15:38.570 --> 00:15:42.310
I knew two other things, but
they were wrong, as it happened.

00:15:42.310 --> 00:15:45.140
So I made him look at the poem.

00:15:45.140 --> 00:15:48.430
'There's a lot of that
going around,' he said.

00:15:48.430 --> 00:15:53.060
And Sweet Baby Jesus he was right.

00:15:53.060 --> 00:15:55.180
He laughed amiably.

00:15:55.180 --> 00:15:59.920
He didn't look as if he thought
bad poems were dangerous,

00:15:59.920 --> 00:16:02.380
the way some poets do.

00:16:02.380 --> 00:16:04.210
If they were baseball executives,

00:16:04.210 --> 00:16:06.610
they'd plot to destroy
sandlots everywhere

00:16:06.610 --> 00:16:10.550
so that the game can
be saved from children.

00:16:10.550 --> 00:16:14.810
Of course later that night he
fired his pianist in mid-number

00:16:14.810 --> 00:16:17.170
and flurried him from the stand.

00:16:17.170 --> 00:16:19.880
'We've suffered a diminuendo
in personnel,

00:16:19.880 --> 00:16:25.200
he explained, and
the band played on."

00:16:25.200 --> 00:16:27.000
Thank you.

00:16:27.000 --> 00:16:33.880
