00:17:11.480 --> 00:17:13.280
Welcome Ahkei.

00:17:13.280 --> 00:17:19.040
[ Applause ]

00:17:19.040 --> 00:17:21.160
&gt;&gt; Good morning.

00:17:21.160 --> 00:17:22.460
&gt;&gt; Good morning.

00:17:22.460 --> 00:17:24.260
&gt;&gt; It's always a pleasure to
be onstage representing Poetry

00:17:24.260 --> 00:17:27.800
Out Loud, whether it's a state
champion, national champion,

00:17:27.800 --> 00:17:30.160
or just starting off as nothing.

00:17:30.160 --> 00:17:33.570
When I first started Poetry Out
Loud, I was just a student trying

00:17:33.570 --> 00:17:36.600
to get an A in my English class.

00:17:36.600 --> 00:17:39.960
[Laughter] But reading the poems
along the way sparked something

00:17:39.960 --> 00:17:41.270
inside of me.

00:17:41.270 --> 00:17:44.070
I began to fall in love
with the thought of poetry,

00:17:44.070 --> 00:17:47.300
and how I connected with some
of the poems that I ran across.

00:17:47.300 --> 00:17:51.120
Excitement grew for the next time
I would be able to get onstage

00:17:51.120 --> 00:17:53.210
and display this passion.

00:17:53.210 --> 00:17:57.700 position:56%
Three years of my high school career
consisted of me learning the ins

00:17:57.700 --> 00:18:01.110
and outs of this thing
called "Poetry Out Loud".

00:18:01.110 --> 00:18:03.280
Winning it all seemed like a dream.

00:18:03.280 --> 00:18:05.100
Thinking of it was like
watching the quarterback

00:18:05.100 --> 00:18:08.130
of the winning Super Bowl team
hold up the trophy and say,

00:18:08.130 --> 00:18:10.950
"I'm going to Disneyland."

00:18:10.950 --> 00:18:12.250
[Laughter] But when I
got the chance to hold

00:18:12.250 --> 00:18:14.290
that trophy, I became speechless.

00:18:14.290 --> 00:18:16.880
The moment was so bittersweet.

00:18:16.880 --> 00:18:19.230
Because it wasn't just about
the title, it was about getting

00:18:19.230 --> 00:18:21.760 position:56%
on the stage and doing what I loved.

00:18:21.760 --> 00:18:26.280
It was sharing life-changing
experiences with the poetic family

00:18:26.280 --> 00:18:28.240
that I could never forget.

00:18:28.240 --> 00:18:32.080
These people made it so easy to
enjoy the moments offstage in order

00:18:32.080 --> 00:18:35.020
to be ready for the moment onstage.

00:18:35.020 --> 00:18:39.200 position:56%
These poets are a group of champions
waiting to change the world.

00:18:39.200 --> 00:18:40.500
I'm so grateful

00:18:40.500 --> 00:18:42.080
for the opportunities
this competition has laid

00:18:42.080 --> 00:18:43.850
out for us as artists.

00:18:43.850 --> 00:18:48.030
I am Ahkei, but we
are Poetry Out Loud.

00:18:48.030 --> 00:18:50.420
Today I will be reciting
two poems for you.

00:18:50.420 --> 00:18:52.820
The first one is called

00:18:52.820 --> 00:18:56.070
"Always Something More
Beautiful," by Stephen Dunn.

00:18:56.070 --> 00:18:59.880
And this poem it really resonates
with like the cores of how Poetry

00:18:59.880 --> 00:19:03.700
Out Loud goes, the race of
what Poetry Out Loud really is,

00:19:03.700 --> 00:19:05.510
and you'll really understand
as I begin to recite.

00:19:05.510 --> 00:19:11.510
[ Silence ]

00:19:11.510 --> 00:19:15.280
"This time I came to the starting
place with my best running shoes,

00:19:15.280 --> 00:19:19.680
and pure speed held back for
the finish, came with only love

00:19:19.680 --> 00:19:22.600
of the clock and the
underfooting and the other runners.

00:19:22.600 --> 00:19:24.610
Each of us would be
testing excellence

00:19:24.610 --> 00:19:27.610
and endurance in the other runners.

00:19:27.610 --> 00:19:33.900 position:56%
Though in the past I'd often veer
off to follow some feral distraction

00:19:33.900 --> 00:19:41.020 position:56%
down a side path, allowing myself to
pursue something odd or beautiful,

00:19:41.020 --> 00:19:46.350 position:56%
becoming acquainted with some of the
ways not to blame myself for failing

00:19:46.350 --> 00:19:52.310
to succeed, I had come to believe
what's beautiful had more to do

00:19:52.310 --> 00:19:56.720
with daring to take yourself
seriously, to stay the course,

00:19:56.720 --> 00:19:59.200
whatever the course might be.

00:19:59.200 --> 00:20:03.100
The guy in the front seemed
ready to fade, his long,

00:20:03.100 --> 00:20:06.850
graceful stride shortening
as I came up along his side.

00:20:06.850 --> 00:20:10.260
I was sure now I'd at
least exceed my best time.

00:20:10.260 --> 00:20:13.660
But the guy with the famous final
kick already had already begun

00:20:13.660 --> 00:20:14.960
his move.

00:20:14.960 --> 00:20:20.920
"Beautiful," I heard a spectator
say, as if something inevitable,

00:20:20.920 --> 00:20:24.140
again, coming from nowhere
was again on its way.

00:20:24.140 --> 00:20:25.940
Thank you.

00:20:25.940 --> 00:20:34.190
[ Applause ]

00:20:34.190 --> 00:20:36.750
This next one is actually one
of my favorite poems to do.

00:20:36.750 --> 00:20:39.690
I started my Poetry Out
Loud career with this poem.

00:20:39.690 --> 00:20:41.510
It's called "Football"
by Louis Jenkins.

00:20:41.510 --> 00:20:46.100
[ Silence ]

00:20:46.100 --> 00:20:48.900
"I take the snap from the center,
fake to the right, fade back.

00:20:48.900 --> 00:20:50.200
I've got protection.

00:20:50.200 --> 00:20:52.370
I've got a receiver open downfield.

00:20:52.370 --> 00:20:54.990
What the hell is this?

00:20:54.990 --> 00:21:00.350
This isn't a football, it's a
shoe, a man's brown leather oxford,

00:21:00.350 --> 00:21:05.700
a cousin to a football maybe,
the same skin, but not the same,

00:21:05.700 --> 00:21:09.140
a thing made for the
earth, not the air.

00:21:09.140 --> 00:21:12.780
See, I realize that this is a
world where anything is possible

00:21:12.780 --> 00:21:15.030
and I understand, also,
that one often has

00:21:15.030 --> 00:21:17.250
to make do with what one has.

00:21:17.250 --> 00:21:23.440 position:56%
I have eaten pancakes, for instance,
with that clear corn syrup on them

00:21:23.440 --> 00:21:29.480
because there was no maple syrup;
and they weren't very good.

00:21:29.480 --> 00:21:31.930
Well, anyway, this is different.

00:21:31.930 --> 00:21:34.970 position:56%
My man downfield is waving his arms.

00:21:34.970 --> 00:21:40.200
One has certain responsibilities,
one has to make choices.

00:21:40.200 --> 00:21:44.600
This isn't right and I'm
not going to throw it."

00:21:44.600 --> 00:21:46.400
Thank you.

00:21:46.400 --> 00:21:53.040
[ Applause ]

