them, which is amazing.

00:27:54.990 --> 00:27:56.410
Not these guys, maybe.

00:27:56.410 --> 00:27:59.060
But yes, if you guys don't mind,
Nealy, we'll start with you

00:27:59.060 --> 00:28:02.570
and we'll just maybe come up in a
little sort of little rolling roll.

00:28:02.570 --> 00:28:04.190
You go first.

00:28:04.190 --> 00:28:06.370
[ Silence ]

00:28:06.370 --> 00:28:09.600
&gt;&gt; Well, you go on there
and there are so many poems

00:28:09.600 --> 00:28:12.060
that it seems overwhelming.

00:28:12.060 --> 00:28:16.510
And for the most part,
I -- whenever I began,

00:28:16.510 --> 00:28:19.320
I just started picking
random letters on --

00:28:19.320 --> 00:28:20.790
because it's alphabetized.

00:28:20.790 --> 00:28:22.680
And so I'd pick a random
letter, and I would look

00:28:22.680 --> 00:28:24.870
through the poems on that letter.

00:28:24.870 --> 00:28:30.550 position:56%
Then as I got more involved, I would
find works that I found on my own

00:28:30.550 --> 00:28:32.680
that I enjoyed and related to.

00:28:32.680 --> 00:28:38.830
And if it wasn't on the anthology,
I would go and find related works

00:28:38.830 --> 00:28:41.820
that relate back to that poem.

00:28:41.820 --> 00:28:46.410
How I picked my poems this
year specifically, I --

00:28:46.410 --> 00:28:49.740
with "Degrees of Gray," I
come from West Virginia,

00:28:49.740 --> 00:28:52.740
which is a coalmining state.

00:28:52.740 --> 00:28:57.160
And even though it takes place
outside of West Virginia,

00:28:57.160 --> 00:29:01.080
I know those towns that I talk
about in "Degrees of Gray".

00:29:01.080 --> 00:29:05.140
And there's something
so personal about it.

00:29:05.140 --> 00:29:12.780 position:56%
And with "Passing", it was also very
personal where since I am biracial

00:29:12.780 --> 00:29:19.180 position:56%
and I can pass, and that's something
that has always bothered me,

00:29:19.180 --> 00:29:21.600
but I've never been able
to put it into words.

00:29:21.600 --> 00:29:25.920
So after reading "Passing",
it was someone understands me,

00:29:25.920 --> 00:29:28.160
and now I can vocalize this.

00:29:28.160 --> 00:29:30.510
And that's how I picked
mine this year.

00:29:30.510 --> 00:29:37.500
[ Applause ]

00:29:37.500 --> 00:29:40.740
&gt;&gt; Well, mine were mostly
by accident the first year.

00:29:40.740 --> 00:29:45.860
There's an option on the website
that says, "Find random poem."

00:29:45.860 --> 00:29:48.780
[Laughs] And so basically because
I didn't want to have to go

00:29:48.780 --> 00:29:52.280 position:56%
through the whole anthology, or like
go by letter and then be like, "Oh,

00:29:52.280 --> 00:29:53.580
I didn't check that letter.

00:29:53.580 --> 00:29:55.310
That's such a great poem,
why didn't I do that,"

00:29:55.310 --> 00:29:57.930
I would just click
"random" and read it.

00:29:57.930 --> 00:30:00.470
If it didn't inspire me by
like the first couple lines,

00:30:00.470 --> 00:30:03.600 position:56%
I'd be like, "No, next, next, next."

00:30:03.600 --> 00:30:07.120
And so the first year, that's
really how I found those poems.

00:30:07.120 --> 00:30:12.600
It's just I kind of waited to see
something that would inspire me.

00:30:12.600 --> 00:30:15.300
And it's not that I stopped
doing that as I went on,

00:30:15.300 --> 00:30:16.640 position:56%
because I've done it all four years.

00:30:16.640 --> 00:30:23.350
But by the time I got to the
year that took me to nationals,

00:30:23.350 --> 00:30:26.640
"Mingus at the Showplace" had
been done by a girl in my school

00:30:26.640 --> 00:30:29.130
who didn't advance, but
I just loved the poem.

00:30:29.130 --> 00:30:30.790
It was just so interesting.

00:30:30.790 --> 00:30:33.530
I didn't understand
it when she said it.

00:30:33.530 --> 00:30:36.220
And so that really
bothered me because I wanted

00:30:36.220 --> 00:30:37.520
to be able to understand it.

00:30:37.520 --> 00:30:38.930
So I went and I looked
it up, and I read it,

00:30:38.930 --> 00:30:40.560
and I read it, and I read it.

00:30:40.560 --> 00:30:43.420
And so that's how I decided,
"I'm going to do this."

00:30:43.420 --> 00:30:46.500
"For the Young Who Want To"
was completely by accident,

00:30:46.500 --> 00:30:48.310
just through the anthology
and I read it,

00:30:48.310 --> 00:30:50.110
and I was like, "This is awesome.

00:30:50.110 --> 00:30:51.410
I need to do this."

00:30:51.410 --> 00:30:53.250
You know, I just -- I
understood it so well.

00:30:53.250 --> 00:30:56.460
And my first poem that I
didn't recite was "Echo".

00:30:56.460 --> 00:31:00.310
And so that was -- I had come
across it a previous year,

00:31:00.310 --> 00:31:01.720
and then I heard someone recite it.

00:31:01.720 --> 00:31:05.260
And I love Christina
Rossetti like as a poet.

00:31:05.260 --> 00:31:08.100
So I just -- I really wanted to do
something by her, and to be able

00:31:08.100 --> 00:31:09.770
to kind of get into that mindset.

00:31:09.770 --> 00:31:12.000
So that's how I chose them,

00:31:12.000 --> 00:31:14.940
mostly by accident, and
some on purpose, so.

00:31:14.940 --> 00:31:16.740
[Laughs]

00:31:16.740 --> 00:31:24.040
[ Applause ]

00:31:24.040 --> 00:31:26.760
&gt;&gt; That's exactly how I feel
about picking the poems.

00:31:26.760 --> 00:31:29.130
Like it is such a long process.

00:31:29.130 --> 00:31:34.820
It's like I had to dedicate
myself like to a whole night

00:31:34.820 --> 00:31:36.120
of just picking out poems.

00:31:36.120 --> 00:31:38.010
It's literally like a
five-hour process for me.

00:31:38.010 --> 00:31:41.820
Because it's literally reading
through poems in the anthology,

00:31:41.820 --> 00:31:44.130
and it's like, "Oh, no, this
one is about a dog in a house.

00:31:44.130 --> 00:31:46.870
I don't have a dog so I don't
want to talk about that one."

00:31:46.870 --> 00:31:49.010
But mostly I do it very
methodically, though.

00:31:49.010 --> 00:31:51.560
I always want to find like a
fun poem to do, because I feel

00:31:51.560 --> 00:31:53.360
like you should have
fun with poetry,

00:31:53.360 --> 00:31:55.120
and I feel like that's what
a lot of people forget.

00:31:55.120 --> 00:31:57.230
They feel like -- again like
I said at first they felt

00:31:57.230 --> 00:31:58.850
like it's just a bunch
of boring poems.

00:31:58.850 --> 00:32:01.420
But a lot of those poems on
there are actually really fun.

00:32:01.420 --> 00:32:03.800
And then again at the same
time, I like to find poems

00:32:03.800 --> 00:32:05.100
that I really connect with.

00:32:05.100 --> 00:32:08.090
So it'll be those poems where I'm
like, "Oh, my God, this is me.

00:32:08.090 --> 00:32:09.390
This is me.

00:32:09.390 --> 00:32:10.690
I should have written this."

00:32:10.690 --> 00:32:12.050
So those are the ones where
I'd probably be like, "Okay;

00:32:12.050 --> 00:32:15.360
I want to do this one," because
it's easier to do and recite poems

00:32:15.360 --> 00:32:16.980
that you actually relate to,

00:32:16.980 --> 00:32:20.230
but it is a long process
to pick a poem out.

00:32:20.230 --> 00:32:21.530
But yes, that's my process, though.

