00:34:16.060 --> 00:34:17.360
&gt;&gt; Oh, my goodness.

00:34:17.360 --> 00:34:21.630
So well first of all,
you just read it a lot.

00:34:21.630 --> 00:34:25.370
And if you have a poem that
you connect with, it's easier.

00:34:25.370 --> 00:34:29.170
It sounds magical and
weird to explain,

00:34:29.170 --> 00:34:32.920
but there's something
behind clicking with it.

00:34:32.920 --> 00:34:34.660
You understand it.

00:34:34.660 --> 00:34:38.210
Then you go through and
you mark out what it means.

00:34:38.210 --> 00:34:42.520
You do research, you find out all
of the ins and outs of the poem.

00:34:42.520 --> 00:34:45.860
And then you just recite
it over and over again.

00:34:45.860 --> 00:34:50.340 position:56%
I work with my theater teacher, and
I do it for my parents all the time.

00:34:50.340 --> 00:34:55.120
I think they can recite all of my
poems as well, including my dog.

00:34:55.120 --> 00:34:57.790
So he gets really rambunctious.

00:34:57.790 --> 00:35:02.090
And sometimes it helps because it
helps me deal with distractions

00:35:02.090 --> 00:35:03.790
that might happen in the audience.

00:35:03.790 --> 00:35:08.640
So as he's like freaking out,
I -- it makes me focus more.

00:35:08.640 --> 00:35:12.900
So it's just repetition and
understanding is how I do it.

00:35:12.900 --> 00:35:15.100
&gt;&gt; Eleanor Billington:
Marta or Ahkei,

00:35:15.100 --> 00:35:18.500
do you guys want to
speak to that too?

00:35:18.500 --> 00:35:19.800
Yes.

00:35:19.800 --> 00:35:21.100
&gt;&gt; Yes.

00:35:21.100 --> 00:35:22.400
&gt;&gt; Eleanor Billington: Okay.

00:35:22.400 --> 00:35:23.700
&gt;&gt; I -- it's repetition, like she
said, it really is repetition.

00:35:23.700 --> 00:35:25.000
I mean, you sit there, you
print it out, and you just --

00:35:25.000 --> 00:35:26.880
you kind of read it
the first couple times.

00:35:26.880 --> 00:35:29.980
And then you're like, "Okay; I'm
going to recite the first stanza.

00:35:29.980 --> 00:35:31.930
Crap, what was the word, you know?

00:35:31.930 --> 00:35:33.860
And you're just kind of,
like -- it's just, you know,

00:35:33.860 --> 00:35:35.360
you have to like get into it.

00:35:35.360 --> 00:35:38.030
And so you kind of just go
stanza by stanza is what I do.

00:35:38.030 --> 00:35:40.960
And then once I feel like
I have it memorized enough,

00:35:40.960 --> 00:35:44.650 position:56%
maybe not to recite it right off the
bat, but to remember it slowly piece

00:35:44.650 --> 00:35:48.370
by piece, and even if I have
to pause and be like, "Okay;

00:35:48.370 --> 00:35:51.460
and the next line rhymes with
this word, so it's this."

00:35:51.460 --> 00:35:53.910
I write it down, because
it really helps me.

00:35:53.910 --> 00:35:57.560
I heard a rumor one time
that before you play shows,

00:35:57.560 --> 00:35:59.760
if you write down your lyrics,
you remember them better.

00:35:59.760 --> 00:36:01.820
And so that's what I've
been doing for my shows.

00:36:01.820 --> 00:36:04.220
And I decided, "Why not do
it with poetry as well?"

00:36:04.220 --> 00:36:06.040
And it actually really works
because there's something

00:36:06.040 --> 00:36:09.890
about your handwriting and
seeing the words come out slowly

00:36:09.890 --> 00:36:11.520
as you're -- you know, not
that you're speaking them,

00:36:11.520 --> 00:36:12.990
but you're just writing
them out yourself.

00:36:12.990 --> 00:36:15.910
There's something that really
helps me remember in that.

00:36:15.910 --> 00:36:17.640
So that's how I do that.

00:36:17.640 --> 00:36:19.440
Yes.

00:36:19.440 --> 00:36:23.860
