00:38:40.080 --> 00:38:42.680
to get a job'," you
know, like, "Okay."

00:38:42.680 --> 00:38:44.890
So my inspiration for
that was really kind

00:38:44.890 --> 00:38:47.960
of just I really understood
what they were talking about.

00:38:47.960 --> 00:38:52.060
And I was like, "I want to do this
because it really is good advice."

00:38:52.060 --> 00:38:55.110
You know, talent is an
invention you have to work at it.

00:38:55.110 --> 00:38:58.560
So I thought it was really
great advice for myself.

00:38:58.560 --> 00:39:01.490
And I wanted to share it because I
knew that I'd be in a room full of,

00:39:01.490 --> 00:39:04.220
you know, writers,
artists, poets, everything.

00:39:04.220 --> 00:39:07.770
So I just felt like I
really needed it to be said.

00:39:07.770 --> 00:39:12.110
"Mingus at the Showplace" --
there's just this element of,

00:39:12.110 --> 00:39:16.720
like childish wonder to it that
I really loved because, you know,

00:39:16.720 --> 00:39:19.520
this -- and it's -- there's
also so much uncertainty.

00:39:19.520 --> 00:39:21.900
You know, this kid
like worships Mingus.

00:39:21.900 --> 00:39:23.270
And, you know, Mingus
is just this kind

00:39:23.270 --> 00:39:26.520
of this larger than life person.

00:39:26.520 --> 00:39:28.530
And then, you know, at
the end, he's, you know,

00:39:28.530 --> 00:39:31.780
dismissing his staff and, you
know, just a normal human being.

00:39:31.780 --> 00:39:33.390
And you get to kind of see
a little aspect of that.

00:39:33.390 --> 00:39:35.710
And I really loved
that about, you know,

00:39:35.710 --> 00:39:37.490
this kid who thinks he's
got it all figured out.

00:39:37.490 --> 00:39:41.660
He's like, "Oh, I'm 17 and I'm
so miserable," and, you know,

00:39:41.660 --> 00:39:44.780
"I suck at writing poetry,"
you know, just stuff like that.

00:39:44.780 --> 00:39:47.080
So there's really so many
little aspects to it.

00:39:47.080 --> 00:39:50.380
And I loved that the poem itself
never really completed any

00:39:50.380 --> 00:39:52.510
of those aspects, it just
left you figure to them

00:39:52.510 --> 00:39:55.860
as the kid himself
is figuring them out.

00:39:55.860 --> 00:39:57.740
So I really loved that about it.

00:39:57.740 --> 00:39:59.530
And I, again, felt like
it needed to be said.

00:39:59.530 --> 00:40:04.530
So really the inspiration for
reciting is more just when you feel

00:40:04.530 --> 00:40:06.720
that something needs to be
shared with other people,

00:40:06.720 --> 00:40:09.330
and when you love it because you
feel like you can just say it.

00:40:09.330 --> 00:40:12.310
And I think that's really
what most of the inspiration

00:40:12.310 --> 00:40:14.510
for reciting comes from, so.

00:40:14.510 --> 00:40:20.790
[ Background Sounds ]

00:40:20.790 --> 00:40:26.590
&gt;&gt; Well, like I said, where I came
from helped with "Degrees of Gray",

00:40:26.590 --> 00:40:30.690
and who I am helped
inspire me for "Passing".

00:40:30.690 --> 00:40:36.190
But what keeps me reciting, and
what keeps me interested is there's

00:40:36.190 --> 00:40:39.780
personal growth that happens
every time you read a poem.

00:40:39.780 --> 00:40:42.770
And then a little bit more
happens whenever you memorize it.

00:40:42.770 --> 00:40:46.120
And then whenever you get to
share it with other people,

00:40:46.120 --> 00:40:49.840
you learn about literature,
and you learn about yourself.

00:40:49.840 --> 00:40:52.500
Sometimes I read a
poem, and I just have

00:40:52.500 --> 00:40:55.600 position:56%
to ask myself, "Why do I like this?"

00:40:55.600 --> 00:40:59.130
And so I learn more about
myself with other people's work.

00:40:59.130 --> 00:41:04.700
And it gives me new ways to relate
to myself and to other people.

00:41:04.700 --> 00:41:09.120
And you find out about so many
different aspects of the world

00:41:09.120 --> 00:41:12.500
and views every time
you read a new poem.

00:41:12.500 --> 00:41:16.510
So that's why I keep reciting,
and keep reading poetry.

00:41:16.510 --> 00:41:21.500
[ Silence ]

00:41:21.500 --> 00:41:25.740
&gt;&gt; My inspiration goes
back to, of course,

00:41:25.740 --> 00:41:27.990
the poems that we connect to.

00:41:27.990 --> 00:41:31.390
It's one of those things -- and
I believe Nealy said it earlier,

00:41:31.390 --> 00:41:34.790
she said it's like the
things that you want to say,

00:41:34.790 --> 00:41:36.490
but you don't know how
to put it into words,

00:41:36.490 --> 00:41:37.890
and it's all right there in a poem.

00:41:37.890 --> 00:41:41.010
So it's like one of those things
where it's like you can't wait

00:41:41.010 --> 00:41:43.300
to really express that
part of yourself.

00:41:43.300 --> 00:41:45.640
You want to get that
story out of you.

00:41:45.640 --> 00:41:48.270
One of my favorite poems that I
did during the competition was

00:41:48.270 --> 00:41:50.760
"I'm A Fool To Love
You" by Cornelius Eady.

00:41:50.760 --> 00:41:54.330
